# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-zookeeper
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-zookeeper/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper is essentially a service for distributed systems offering a hierarchical key-value store, which is used to provide a distributed configuration service, synchronization service, and naming registry for large distributed systems (see *Use cases*).
[src:apache-zookeeper/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper was a sub-project of Hadoop but is now a top-level Apache project in its own right.
[src:apache-zookeeper/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper's architecture supports high availability through redundant services.
[src:apache-zookeeper/apache-zookeeper] Clients can ask another ZooKeeper leader if the first fails to answer.
[src:apache-zookeeper/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper nodes store their data in a hierarchical name space, like a file system or a tree data structure.
[src:apache-zookeeper/apache-zookeeper] Clients can read from and write to the nodes and in this way have a shared configuration service.
[src:apache-zookeeper/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper can be viewed as an atomic broadcast system, through which updates are totally ordered.
[src:apache-zookeeper/apache-zookeeper] The ZooKeeper Atomic Broadcast (ZAB) protocol is the core of the system.
[src:apache-zookeeper/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper is used by companies including Yelp, Rackspace, Yahoo, Odnoklassniki, Reddit, NetApp SolidFire, Meta, Twitter and eBay as well as open source enterprise search systems like Solr and distributed database systems like Apache Pinot.
[src:apache-zookeeper/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper is modeled after Google's Chubby lock service and was originally developed at Yahoo! for streamlining the processes running on big-data clusters by storing the status in local log files on the ZooKeeper servers.
[src:apache-zookeeper/apache-zookeeper] These servers communicate with client machines to deliver the required information.
[src:apache-zookeeper/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper was developed to address issues that emerged during the deployment of distributed big-data applications.
[src:apache-zookeeper/apache-zookeeper] The services in the cluster are replicated and stored on a set of servers (called an "ensemble"), each of which maintains an in-memory database containing the entire data tree of state as well as a transaction log and snapshots stored persistently.
[src:apache-zookeeper/apache-zookeeper] Multiple client applications can connect to a server, and each client maintains a TCP connection through which it sends requests and heartbeats and receives responses and watch events for monitoring.
[src:apache-zookeeper/apache-zookeeper] In addition to the client libraries included with the ZooKeeper distribution, several third-party libraries, including Apache Curator and Kazoo, extend ZooKeeper's capabilities.
[src:apache-zookeeper/apache-zookeeper] These libraries offer enhanced ease of use, additional features and support for a broader range of programming languages.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] Every read receives the most recent write or an error.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] Consistency means that all clients see the same data at the same time, no matter which node they connect to.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] This is the definition of availability in CAP theorem as defined by Gilbert and Lynch.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] The system continues to operate despite an arbitrary number of messages being dropped (or delayed) by the network between nodes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] Thus, if there is a network partition, one has to choose between consistency or availability.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] During times of normal operations, a data store covers all three.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] No distributed system is safe from network failures, thus network partitioning generally has to be tolerated.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] In the presence of a partition, one is then left with two options: consistency or availability.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] When choosing consistency over availability, the system will return an error or a time out if particular information cannot be guaranteed to be up to date due to network partitioning.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] When choosing availability over consistency, the system will always process the query and try to return the most recent available version of the information, even if it cannot guarantee it is up to date due to network partitioning.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] In the absence of a network partition, both availability and consistency can be satisfied.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] CouchDB, Cassandra, and ScyllaDB are examples of AP databases.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] There are no NoSQL databases one would classify as CA.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] Most modern distributed databases offer configuration options for both consistency and availability.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] Some cloud services choose strong consistency but use worldwide private fiber networks and GPS clock synchronization to minimize the frequency of network partitions.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] Finally, consistent shared-nothing architectures may use techniques such as geographic sharding to maintain availability of data owned by the queried node, but without being available for arbitrary requests during a network partition.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] According to computer scientist Eric Brewer of the University of California, Berkeley, the theorem first appeared in autumn 1998.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] It was published as the CAP principle in 1999 and presented as a conjecture by Brewer at the 2000 Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC).
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] In 2002, Seth Gilbert and Nancy Lynch of MIT published a formal proof of Brewer's conjecture, rendering it a theorem.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] In 2012, Brewer clarified some of his positions, including why the often-used "two out of three" concept can be somewhat misleading because system designers only need to sacrifice consistency or availability in the presence of partitions; partition management and recovery techniques exist.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] Brewer also noted the different definition of consistency used in the CAP theorem relative to the definition used in ACID.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] A similar theorem stating the trade-off between consistency and availability in distributed systems had been published by Birman and Friedman in 1996.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] Birman and Friedman's result had restricted this lower bound to non-commuting operations.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] The PACELC theorem, introduced in 2010, builds on CAP by stating that even in the absence of partitioning, there is another trade-off between latency and consistency.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] PACELC means, if partition (P) happens, the trade-off is between availability (A) and consistency (C); Else (E), the trade-off is between latency (L) and consistency (C).
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] Some experts like Marc Brooker argue that the CAP theorem is particularly relevant in intermittently connected environments, such as those related to the Internet of Things (IoT) and mobile applications.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] In these contexts, devices may become partitioned due to challenging physical conditions, such as power outages or when entering confined spaces like elevators.
[src:apache-zookeeper/cap-theorem] For distributed systems, such as cloud applications, it is more appropriate to use the PACELC theorem, which is more comprehensive and considers trade-offs such as latency and consistency even in the absence of network partitions.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] A fundamental problem in distributed computing and multi-agent systems is to achieve overall system reliability in the presence of a number of faulty processes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] This often requires coordinating processes to reach **consensus**, or agree on some data value that is needed during computation.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Example applications of consensus include agreeing on what transactions to commit to a database in which order, state machine replication, and atomic broadcasts.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Real-world applications often requiring consensus include cloud computing, clock synchronization, PageRank, opinion formation, smart power grids, state estimation, control of UAVs (and multiple robots/agents in general), load balancing, blockchain, and others.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] The consensus problem requires agreement among a number of processes (or agents) on a single data value.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Some of the processes (agents) may fail or be unreliable in other ways, so consensus protocols must be fault-tolerant or resilient.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] The processes must put forth their candidate values, communicate with one another, and agree on a single consensus value.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] The consensus problem is a fundamental problem in controlling multi-agent systems.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] One approach to generating consensus is for all processes (agents) to agree on a majority value.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In this context, a majority requires at least one more than half of the available votes (where each process is given a vote).
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] However, one or more faulty processes may skew the resultant outcome such that consensus may not be reached or may be reached incorrectly.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Protocols that solve consensus problems are designed to deal with a limited number of faulty processes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] These protocols must satisfy several requirements to be useful.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] For instance, a trivial protocol could have all processes output binary value 1.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] This is not useful; thus, the requirement is modified such that the production must depend on the input.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] That is, the output value of a consensus protocol must be the input value of some process.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Another requirement is that a process may decide upon an output value only once, and this decision is irrevocable.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] A method is correct in an execution if it does not experience a failure.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] A consensus protocol tolerating halting failures must satisfy the following properties.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Eventually, every correct process decides some value.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Every correct process must agree on the same value.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Variations on the definition of *integrity* may be appropriate, according to the application.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] For example, a weaker type of integrity would be for the decision value to equal a value that some correct process proposed – not necessarily all of them.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] There is also a condition known as **validity** in the literature which refers to the property that a message sent by a process must be delivered.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] A protocol that can correctly guarantee consensus amongst n processes of which at most t fail is said to be *t-resilient*.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In evaluating the performance of consensus protocols two factors of interest are *running time* and *message complexity*.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Running time is given in Big O notation in the number of rounds of message exchange as a function of some input parameters (typically the number of processes and/or the size of the input domain).
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Message complexity refers to the amount of message traffic that is generated by the protocol.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Other factors may include memory usage and the size of messages.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Varying models of computation may define a "consensus problem".
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Some models may deal with fully connected graphs, while others may deal with rings and trees.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In some models message authentication is allowed, whereas in others processes are completely anonymous.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Shared memory models in which processes communicate by accessing objects in shared memory are also an important area of research.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In most models of communication protocol participants communicate through *authenticated channels.* This means that messages are not anonymous, and receivers know the source of every message they receive.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Some models assume a stronger, *transferable* form of authentication, where each *message* is signed by the sender, so that a receiver knows not just the immediate source of every message, but the participant that initially created the message.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] This stronger type of authentication is achieved by digital signatures, and when this stronger form of authentication is available, protocols can tolerate a larger number of faults.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] The two different authentication models are often called *oral communication* and *written communication* models.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In an oral communication model, the immediate source of information is known, whereas in stronger, written communication models, every step along the receiver learns not just the immediate source of the message, but the communication history of the message.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In the most traditional **single-value** consensus protocols such as Paxos, cooperating nodes agree on a single value such as an integer, which may be of variable size so as to encode useful metadata such as a transaction committed to a database.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] A special case of the single-value consensus problem, called **binary consensus**, restricts the input, and hence the output domain, to a single binary digit {0,1}.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] While not highly useful by themselves, binary consensus protocols are often useful as building blocks in more general consensus protocols, especially for asynchronous consensus.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In **multi-valued** consensus protocols such as Multi-Paxos and Raft, the goal is to agree on not just a single value but a series of values over time, forming a progressively-growing history.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] While multi-valued consensus may be achieved naively by running multiple iterations of a single-valued consensus protocol in succession, many optimizations and other considerations such as reconfiguration support can make multi-valued consensus protocols more efficient in practice.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] There are two types of failures a process may undergo, a crash failure or a Byzantine failure.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] A *crash failure* occurs when a process abruptly stops and does not resume.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] *Byzantine failure*s are failures in which absolutely no conditions are imposed.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] For example, they may occur as a result of the malicious actions of an adversary.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] A process that experiences a Byzantine failure may send contradictory or conflicting data to other processes, or it may sleep and then resume activity after a lengthy delay.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Of the two types of failures, Byzantine failures are far more disruptive.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Thus, a consensus protocol tolerating Byzantine failures must be resilient to every possible error that can occur.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] must have been proposed by some correct process.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] The consensus problem may be considered in the case of asynchronous or synchronous systems.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] While real world communications are often inherently asynchronous, it is more practical and often easier to model synchronous systems, given that asynchronous systems naturally involve more issues than synchronous ones.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In synchronous systems, it is assumed that all communications proceed in *rounds*.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In one round, a process may send all the messages it requires, while receiving all messages from other processes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In this manner, no message from one round may influence any messages sent within the same round.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In a fully asynchronous message-passing distributed system, in which at least one process may have a *crash failure*, it has been proven in the famous 1985 **FLP impossibility result** by Fischer, Lynch and Paterson that a deterministic algorithm for achieving consensus is impossible.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] This impossibility result derives from worst-case scheduling scenarios, which are unlikely to occur in practice except in adversarial situations such as an intelligent denial-of-service attacker in the network.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In most normal situations, process scheduling has a degree of natural randomness.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In an asynchronous model, some forms of failures can be handled by a synchronous consensus protocol.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] For instance, the loss of a communication link may be modeled as a process which has suffered a Byzantine failure.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Randomized consensus algorithms can circumvent the FLP impossibility result by achieving both safety and liveness with overwhelming probability, even under worst-case scheduling scenarios such as an intelligent denial-of-service attacker in the network.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Consensus algorithms traditionally assume that the set of participating nodes is fixed and given at the outset: that is, that some prior (manual or automatic) configuration process has **permissioned** a particular known group of participants who can authenticate each other as members of the group.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In the absence of such a well-defined, closed group with authenticated members, a Sybil attack against an open consensus group can defeat even a Byzantine consensus algorithm, simply by creating enough virtual participants to overwhelm the fault tolerance threshold.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] A **permissionless** consensus protocol, in contrast, allows anyone in the network to join dynamically and participate without prior permission, but instead imposes a different form of artificial cost or barrier to entry to mitigate the Sybil attack threat.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Motivated in part by the high energy cost of this approach, subsequent permissionless consensus protocols have proposed or adopted other alternative participation rules for Sybil attack protection, such as proof of stake, proof of space, and proof of authority.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Three agreement problems of interest are as follows.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] A collection of n processes, numbered from 0 to $n-1,$ communicate by sending messages to one another.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] 2. for any two correct processes, each process receives the same value.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] It is also known as The General's Problem.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] For *n* processes in a partially synchronous system (the system alternates between good and bad periods of synchrony), each process chooses a private value.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] 2. all messages sent in a round by a correct process are received in the same round by all correct processes (consistency property).
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] It can be shown that variations of these problems are equivalent in that the solution for a problem in one type of model may be the solution for another problem in another type of model.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] For example, a solution to the Weak Byzantine General problem in a synchronous authenticated message passing model leads to a solution for Weak Interactive Consistency.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] An interactive consistency algorithm can solve the consensus problem by having each process choose the majority value in its consensus vector as its consensus value.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] There is a t-resilient anonymous synchronous protocol which solves the Byzantine Generals problem, if ${\tfrac {t}{n}}<{\tfrac {1}{3}}$ and the Weak Byzantine Generals case where t is the number of failures and n is the number of processes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] For systems with n processors, of which f are Byzantine, it has been shown that there exists no algorithm that solves the consensus problem for $n\leq 3f$ in the *oral-messages model*.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] The proof is constructed by first showing the impossibility for the three-node case $n=3$ and using this result to argue about partitions of processors.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In the *written-messages model* there are protocols that can tolerate $n=f+1$ .
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In a fully asynchronous system there is no consensus solution that can tolerate one or more crash failures even when only requiring the non triviality property.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] This result is sometimes called the FLP impossibility proof named after the authors Michael J.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Fischer, Nancy Lynch, and Mike Paterson who were awarded a Dijkstra Prize for this significant work.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] The FLP result has been mechanically verified to hold even under fairness assumptions.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] However, FLP does not state that consensus can never be reached: merely that under the model's assumptions, no algorithm can always reach consensus in bounded time.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In practice it is highly unlikely to occur.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] The Paxos consensus algorithm by Leslie Lamport, and variants of it such as Raft, are used pervasively in widely deployed distributed and cloud computing systems.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] These algorithms are typically synchronous, dependent on an elected leader to make progress, and tolerate only crashes and not Byzantine failures.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Other protocols, such as Cerberus, have been developed to apply Byzantine fault-tolerant consensus to sharded distributed ledgers and have been the subject of academic analysis.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] An example of a polynomial time binary consensus protocol that tolerates Byzantine failures is the Phase King algorithm by Garay and Berman.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] The algorithm solves consensus in a synchronous message passing model with *n* processes and up to *f* failures, provided *n* > 4*f*.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In the phase king algorithm, there are *f* + 1 phases, with 2 rounds per phase.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Each process keeps track of its preferred output (initially equal to the process's own input value).
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In the first round of each phase each process broadcasts its own preferred value to all other processes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] It then receives the values from all processes and determines which value is the majority value and its count.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In the second round of the phase, the process whose id matches the current phase number is designated the king of the phase.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] The king broadcasts the majority value it observed in the first round and serves as a tie breaker.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Each process then updates its preferred value as follows.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] If the count of the majority value the process observed in the first round is greater than *n*/2 + *f*, the process changes its preference to that majority value; otherwise it uses the phase king's value.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] At the end of *f* + 1 phases the processes output their preferred values.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Google has implemented a distributed lock service library called Chubby.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Chubby maintains lock information in small files which are stored in a replicated database to achieve high availability in the face of failures.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] The database is implemented on top of a fault-tolerant log layer which is based on the Paxos consensus algorithm.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] In this scheme, Chubby clients communicate with the Paxos *master* in order to access/update the replicated log; i.e., read/write to the files.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Many peer-to-peer online real-time strategy games use a modified lockstep protocol as a consensus protocol in order to manage game state between players in a game.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Each game action results in a game state delta broadcast to all other players in the game along with a hash of the total game state.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Each player validates the change by applying the delta to their own game state and comparing the game state hashes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Another well-known approach is called MSR-type algorithms which have been used widely in fields from computer science to control theory.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Bitcoin uses proof of work, a difficulty adjustment function and a reorganization function to achieve permissionless consensus in its open peer-to-peer network.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] To extend bitcoin's blockchain or distributed ledger, *miners* attempt to solve a cryptographic puzzle, where probability of finding a solution is proportional to the computational effort expended in hashes per second.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] The node that first solves such a puzzle has their proposed version of the next block of transactions added to the ledger and eventually accepted by all other nodes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] As any node in the network can attempt to solve the proof-of-work problem, a Sybil attack is infeasible in principle unless the attacker has over 50% of the computational resources of the network.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Ethereum, NEO, STRATIS, ...) use proof of stake, in which nodes compete to append blocks and earn associated rewards in proportion to *stake*, or existing cryptocurrency allocated and locked or *staked* for some time period.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] One advantage of a 'proof of stake' over a 'proof of work' system, is the high energy consumption demanded by the latter.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] As an example, bitcoin mining (2018) is estimated to consume non-renewable energy sources at an amount similar to the entire nations of Czech Republic or Jordan, while the total energy consumption of Ethereum, the largest proof of stake network, is just under that of 205 average US households.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Some cryptocurrencies, such as Ripple, use a system of validating nodes to validate the ledger.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Step 4: the final round requires 80% agreement.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Other participation rules used in permissionless consensus protocols to impose barriers to entry and resist sybil attacks include proof of authority, proof of space, proof of burn, or proof of elapsed time.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Proposed approaches to achieving one-per-person distribution of consensus power for proof of personhood include physical pseudonym parties, social networks, pseudonymized government-issued identities, and biometrics.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] To solve the consensus problem in a shared-memory system, concurrent objects must be introduced.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] A concurrent object, or shared object, is a data structure which helps concurrent processes communicate to reach an agreement.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Traditional implementations using critical sections face the risk of crashing if some process dies inside the critical section or sleeps for an intolerably long time.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Researchers defined wait-freedom as the guarantee that the algorithm completes in a finite number of steps.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] The **consensus number** of a concurrent object is defined to be the maximum number of processes in the system which can reach consensus by the given object in a wait-free implementation.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Objects with a consensus number of n can implement any object with a consensus number of n or lower, but cannot implement any objects with a higher consensus number.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] The consensus numbers form what is called Herlihy's hierarchy of synchronization objects.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] According to the hierarchy, read/write registers cannot solve consensus even in a 2-process system.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] Data structures like stacks and queues can only solve consensus between two processes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/consensus-computer-science] However, some concurrent objects are universal (notated in the table with $\infty$ ), which means they can solve consensus among any number of processes and they can simulate any other objects through an operation sequence.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:apache-zookeeper/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance specifically refers to a system's capability to handle faults without any degradation or downtime.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] In the event of an error, end-users remain unaware of any issues.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Conversely, a system that experiences errors with some interruption in service or graceful degradation of performance is termed 'resilient'.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] In resilience, the system adapts to the error, maintaining service but acknowledging a certain impact on performance.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Typically, fault tolerance describes computer systems, ensuring the overall system remains functional despite hardware or software issues.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Non-computing examples include structures that retain their integrity despite damage from fatigue, corrosion or impact.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] The first known fault-tolerant computer was SAPO, built in 1951 in Czechoslovakia by Antonín Svoboda.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Its basic design was magnetic drums connected via relays, with a voting method of memory error detection (triple modular redundancy).
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Several other machines were developed along this line, mostly for military use.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Computers with a high amount of runtime that would be under heavy use, such as many of the supercomputers used by insurance companies for their probability monitoring.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Most of the development in the so-called LLNM (Long Life, No Maintenance) computing was done by NASA during the 1960s, in preparation for Project Apollo and other research aspects.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] NASA's first machine went into a space observatory, and their second attempt, the JSTAR computer, was used in Voyager.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] This computer had a backup of memory arrays to use memory recovery methods and thus it was called the Jet Propulsion Laboratory Self-Testing-And-Repairing computer.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] It could detect its own errors and fix them or use redundant modules as needed.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] The computer is still working, as of early 2022.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Hyper-dependable computers were pioneered mostly by aircraft manufacturers, nuclear power companies, and the railroad industry in the United States.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] These entities needed computers with massive amounts of uptime that would fail gracefully enough during a fault to allow continued operation, while relying on constant human monitoring of computer output to detect faults.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] IBM developed the first computer of this kind for NASA for guidance of Saturn V rockets.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Later, BNSF, Unisys, and General Electric built their own.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] In the 1970s, much work happened in the field.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] For instance, F14 CADC had built-in self-test and redundancy.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] In general, the early efforts at fault-tolerant designs were focused mainly on internal diagnosis, where a fault would indicate something was failing and a worker could replace it.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] SAPO, for instance, had a method by which faulty memory drums would emit a noise before failure.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Later efforts showed that to be fully effective, the system had to be self-repairing and diagnosing – isolating a fault and then implementing a redundant backup while alerting a need for repair.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] This is known as N-model redundancy, where faults cause automatic fail-safes and a warning to the operator, and it is still the most common form of level one fault-tolerant design in use today.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Voting was another initial method, as discussed above, with multiple redundant backups operating constantly and checking each other's results.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] For example, if four components reported an answer of 5 and one component reported an answer of 6, the other four would "vote" that the fifth component was faulty and have it taken out of service.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] This is called M out of N majority voting.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Historically, the trend has been to move away from N-model and toward M out of N, as the complexity of systems and the difficulty of ensuring the transitive state from fault-negative to fault-positive did not disrupt operations.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers, in 1976 and Stratus Technologies were among the first companies specializing in the design of fault-tolerant computer systems for online transaction processing.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Hardware fault tolerance sometimes requires that broken parts be removed and replaced with new parts while the system is still operational (in computing known as *hot swapping*).
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Such a system implemented with a single backup is known as **single point tolerant** and represents the vast majority of fault-tolerant systems.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] In such systems the mean time between failures should be long enough for the operators to have sufficient time to fix the broken devices (mean time to repair) before the backup also fails.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] It is helpful if the time between failures is as long as possible, but this is not specifically required in a fault-tolerant system.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance is notably successful in computer applications.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers built their entire business on such machines, which used single-point tolerance to create their NonStop systems with uptimes measured in years.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Fail-safe architectures may encompass also the computer software, for example by process replication.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Data formats may also be designed to degrade gracefully.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Hyper Text Markup Language (HTML) for example, is designed to be forward compatible, allowing Web browsers to ignore new and unsupported HTML entities without causing the document to be unusable.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Additionally, proper user interface design mandates that websites provide an optional lightweight front end that does not rely on JavaScript and has a minimal layout, to ensure wide accessibility and outreach.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] A highly fault-tolerant system might continue at the same level of performance even though one or more components have failed.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] For example, a building with a backup electrical generator will provide the same voltage to wall outlets even if the grid power fails.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] A system that is designed to fail safe, or fail-secure, or **fail gracefully**, whether it functions at a reduced level or fails completely, does so in a way that protects people, property, or data from injury, damage, intrusion, or disclosure.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] In computers, a program might fail-safe by executing a graceful exit (as opposed to an uncontrolled crash) to prevent data corruption after an error occurs.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] A similar distinction is made between "failing well" and "failing badly".
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] A system designed to experience **graceful degradation**, or to **fail soft** (used in computing, similar to "fail safe") operates at a reduced level of performance after some component fails.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] For example, if grid power fails, a building may operate lighting at reduced levels or elevators at reduced speeds.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] In computing, if insufficient network bandwidth is available to stream an online video, a lower-resolution version might be streamed in place of the high-resolution version.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Progressive enhancement is another example, where web pages are available in a basic functional format for older, small-screen, or limited-capability web browsers, but in an enhanced version for browsers capable of handling additional technologies or that have a larger display.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] In fault-tolerant computer systems, programs that are considered robust are designed to continue operation despite an error, exception, or invalid input, instead of failing completely.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Software brittleness is the opposite of robustness.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Resilient networks continue to transmit data despite the failure of some links or nodes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Resilient buildings and infrastructure are likewise expected to prevent complete failure in situations like earthquakes, floods, or collisions.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] A system with high failure transparency will alert users that a component failure has occurred, even if it continues to operate with full performance, so that failure can be repaired or imminent complete failure anticipated.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Likewise, a fail-fast component is designed to report at the first point of failure, rather than generating reports when downstream components fail.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] This allows easier diagnosis of the underlying problem, and may prevent improper operation in a broken state.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] A **single fault condition** is a situation where one means for protection against a hazard is defective.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] If a single fault condition results unavoidably in another single fault condition, the two failures are considered one single fault condition.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Providing fault-tolerant design for every component is normally not an option.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Associated redundancy brings a number of penalties: increase in weight, size, power consumption, cost, as well as time to design, verify, and test.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] An example of a component that passes all the tests is a car's occupant restraint system.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] While the *primary* occupant restraint system is not normally thought of, it is gravity.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] If the vehicle rolls over or undergoes severe g-forces, then this primary method of occupant restraint may fail.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Restraining the occupants during such an accident is absolutely critical to safety, so the first test is passed.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Accidents causing occupant ejection were quite common before seat belts, so the second test is passed.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] The cost of a redundant restraint method like seat belts is quite low, both economically and in terms of weight and space, so the third test is passed.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Therefore, adding seat belts to all vehicles is an excellent idea.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Other "supplemental restraint systems", such as airbags, are more expensive and so pass that test by a smaller margin.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] It would also be prohibitively costly to further double-up the main components and they would add considerable weight.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] However, the similarly critical systems for actuating the brakes under driver control are inherently less robust, generally using a cable (which can rust, stretch, jam, or snap) or hydraulic fluid (which can leak, boil and develop bubbles, or absorb water and thus lose effectiveness).
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] The cumulatively unlikely combination of total foot brake failure with the need for harsh braking in an emergency will likely result in a collision, but still one at lower speed than would otherwise have been the case.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] In comparison with the foot pedal activated service brake, the parking brake itself is a less critical item, and unless it is being used as a one-time backup for the footbrake, will not cause immediate danger if it is found to be nonfunctional at the moment of application.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, on shallow gradients, the transmission can be shifted into Park, Reverse or First gear, and the transmission lock / engine compression used to hold it stationary, as there is no need for them to include the sophistication to first bring the vehicle to a halt.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] On motorcycles, a similar level of fail-safety is provided by simpler methods; first, the front and rear brake systems are entirely separate, regardless of their method of activation (that can be cable, rod or hydraulic), allowing one system to fail entirely while leaving the other unaffected.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Fault isolation to the failing component – When a failure occurs, the system must be able to isolate the failure to the offending component.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] This requires the addition of dedicated failure detection mechanisms that exist only for the purpose of fault isolation.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Recovery from a fault condition requires classifying the fault or failing component.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Faults are commonly categorized by their locality (internal or external to the system), cause (natural or human-made), duration (permanent or transient), and effect on system behavior.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Fault containment to prevent propagation of the failure – Some failure mechanisms can cause a system to fail by propagating the failure to the rest of the system.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] An example of this kind of failure is the "rogue transmitter" that can swamp legitimate communication in a system and cause overall system failure.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Firewalls or other mechanisms that isolate a rogue transmitter or failing component to protect the system are required.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Availability of reversion modes, which is the abandonment of recent changes, usually to software, that bring a system back to reasonably proper behavior and function.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] In addition, fault-tolerant systems are characterized in terms of both planned service outages and unplanned service outages.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] These are usually measured at the application level and not just at a hardware level.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] The figure of merit is called availability and is expressed as a percentage.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] For example, a five nines system would statistically provide 99.999% availability.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Fault-tolerant systems are typically based on the concept of redundancy.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Research into the kinds of tolerances needed for critical systems involves a large amount of interdisciplinary work.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] The more complex the system, the more carefully all possible interactions have to be considered and prepared for.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] All implementations of RAID, redundant array of independent disks, except RAID 0, are examples of a fault-tolerant storage device that uses data redundancy.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] A lockstep fault-tolerant machine uses replicated elements operating in parallel.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] At any time, all the replications of each element should be in the same state.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] The same inputs are provided to each replication, and the same outputs are expected.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] The outputs of the replications are compared using a voting circuit.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] A machine with two replications of each element is termed dual modular redundant (DMR).
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can then only detect a mismatch and recovery relies on other methods.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] A machine with three replications of each element is termed triple modular redundant (TMR).
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can determine which replication is in error when a two-to-one vote is observed.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] In this case, the voting circuit can output the correct result, and discard the erroneous version.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] After this, the internal state of the erroneous replication is assumed to be different from that of the other two, and the voting circuit can switch to a DMR mode.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] This model can be applied to any larger number of replications.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Lockstep fault-tolerant machines are most easily made fully synchronous, with each gate of each replication making the same state transition on the same edge of the clock, and the clocks to the replications being exactly in phase.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] However, it is possible to build lockstep systems without this requirement.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Bringing the replications into synchrony requires making their internal stored states the same.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] They can be started from a fixed initial state, such as the reset state.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, the internal state of one replica can be copied to another replica.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] One variant of DMR is **pair-and-spare**.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Two replicated elements operate in lockstep as a pair, with a voting circuit that detects any mismatch between their operations and outputs a signal indicating that there is an error.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Another pair operates exactly the same way.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] A final circuit selects the output of the pair that does not proclaim that it is in error.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Pair-and-spare requires four replicas rather than the three of TMR, but has been used commercially.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] The approach has performance costs: because the technique rewrites code to insert dynamic checks for address validity, execution time will increase by 80% to 500%.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Recovery shepherding is a lightweight technique to enable software programs to recover from otherwise fatal errors such as null pointer dereference and divide by zero.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Comparing to the failure oblivious computing technique, recovery shepherding works on the compiled program binary directly and does not need to recompile to program.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] It uses the just-in-time binary instrumentation framework Pin.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] It attaches to the application process when an error occurs, repairs the execution, tracks the repair effects as the execution continues, contains the repair effects within the application process, and detaches from the process after all repair effects are flushed from the process state.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] It does not interfere with the normal execution of the program and therefore incurs negligible overhead.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] For 17 of 18 systematically collected real world null-dereference and divide-by-zero errors, a prototype implementation enables the application to continue to execute to provide acceptable output and service to its users on the error-triggering inputs.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] The circuit breaker design pattern is a technique to avoid catastrophic failures in distributed systems.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Redundancy is the provision of functional capabilities that would be unnecessary in a fault-free environment.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] This can consist of backup components that automatically "kick in" if one component fails.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] For example, large cargo trucks can lose a tire without any major consequences.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] They have many tires, and no one tire is critical (with the exception of the front tires, which are used to steer, but generally carry less load, each and in total, than the other four to 16, so are less likely to fail).
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] The idea of incorporating redundancy in order to improve the reliability of a system was pioneered by John von Neumann in the 1950s.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Two kinds of redundancy are possible: space redundancy and time redundancy.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy provides additional components, functions, or data items that are unnecessary for fault-free operation.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy is further classified into hardware, software and information redundancy, depending on the type of redundant resources added to the system.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] In time redundancy the computation or data transmission is repeated and the result is compared to a stored copy of the previous result.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] The current terminology for this kind of testing is referred to as In Service Fault Tolerance Testing or ISFTT for short.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] There is a difference between fault tolerance and systems that rarely have problems.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] For instance, the Western Electric crossbar systems had failure rates of two hours per forty years, and therefore were highly *fault resistant*.
[src:apache-zookeeper/fault-tolerance] But when a fault did occur, they stopped operating completely, and therefore were not *fault tolerant*.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Replication in space or in time is often linked to scheduling algorithms.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Access to a replicated entity is typically uniform with access to a single non-replicated entity.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] The replication itself should be transparent to an external user.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] In a failure scenario, a failover of replicas should be hidden as much as possible with respect to quality of service.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] When one leader replica is designated via leader election to process all the requests, the system is using a primary-backup or primary-replica scheme, which is predominant in high-availability clusters.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] In comparison, if any replica can process a request and distribute a new state, the system is using a multi-primary or multi-master scheme.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] In the latter case, some form of distributed concurrency control must be used, such as a distributed lock manager.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Load balancing differs from task replication, since it distributes a load of different computations across machines, and allows a single computation to be dropped in case of failure.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Load balancing, however, sometimes uses data replication (especially multi-master replication) internally, to distribute its data among machines.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Backup differs from replication in that the saved copy of data remains unchanged for a long period of time.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Replicas, on the other hand, undergo frequent updates and quickly lose any historical state.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Replication is one of the oldest and most important topics in the overall area of distributed systems.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Data replication and computation replication both require processes to handle incoming events.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Processes for data replication are passive and operate only to maintain the stored data, reply to read requests and apply updates.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Computation replication is usually performed to provide fault-tolerance, and take over an operation if one component fails.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] In both cases, the underlying needs are to ensure that the replicas see the same events in equivalent orders, so that they stay in consistent states and any replica can respond to queries.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Database replication involves maintaining copies of the same data on multiple machines, typically implemented through three main approaches: single-leader, multi-leader, and leaderless replication.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] In single-leader (also called primary/replica) replication, one database instance is designated as the leader (primary), which handles all write operations.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] The leader logs these updates, which then propagate to replica nodes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Each replica acknowledges receipt of updates, enabling subsequent write operations.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Replicas primarily serve read requests, though they may serve stale data due to replication lag – the delay in propagating changes from the leader.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] In multi-master replication (also called multi-leader), updates can be submitted to any database node, which then propagate to other servers.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] This approach is particularly beneficial in multi-data center deployments, where it enables local write processing while masking inter-data center network latency.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] However, it introduces substantially increased costs and complexity which may make it impractical in some situations.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] The most common challenge that exists in multi-master replication is transactional conflict prevention or resolution when concurrent modifications occur on different leader nodes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Most synchronous (or eager) replication solutions perform conflict prevention, while asynchronous (or lazy) solutions have to perform conflict resolution.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] For instance, if the same record is changed on two nodes simultaneously, an eager replication system would detect the conflict before confirming the commit and abort one of the transactions.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] A lazy replication system would allow both transactions to commit and run a conflict resolution during re-synchronization.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Conflict resolution methods can include techniques like last-write-wins, application-specific logic, or merging concurrent updates.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] However, replication transparency can not always be achieved.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] When data is replicated in a database, they will be constrained by CAP theorem or PACELC theorem.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] In the NoSQL movement, data consistency is usually sacrificed in exchange for other more desired properties, such as availability (A), partition tolerance (P), etc.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Various data consistency models have also been developed to serve as Service Level Agreement (SLA) between service providers and the users.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Active (real-time) storage replication is usually implemented by distributing updates of a block device to several physical hard disks.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] This way, any file system supported by the operating system can be replicated without modification, as the file system code works on a level above the block device driver layer.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] It is implemented either in hardware (in a disk array controller) or in software (in a device driver).
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] The most basic method is disk mirroring, which is typical for locally connected disks.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] The storage industry narrows the definitions, so *mirroring* is a local (short-distance) operation.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] A replication is extendable across a computer network, so that the disks can be located in physically distant locations, and the primary/replica database replication model is usually applied.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] The purpose of replication is to prevent damage from failures or disasters that may occur in one location – or in case such events do occur, to improve the ability to recover data.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] For replication, latency is the key factor because it determines either how far apart the sites can be or the type of replication that can be employed.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] The main characteristic of such cross-site replication is how write operations are handled, through either asynchronous or synchronous replication; synchronous replication needs to wait for the destination server's response in any write operation whereas asynchronous replication does not.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Synchronous replication guarantees "zero data loss" by the means of atomic write operations, where the write operation is not considered complete until acknowledged by both the local and remote storage.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Most applications wait for a write transaction to complete before proceeding with further work, hence overall performance decreases considerably.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Inherently, performance drops proportionally to distance, as minimum latency is dictated by the speed of light.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] For 10 km distance, the fastest possible roundtrip takes 67 μs, whereas an entire local cached write completes in about 10–20 μs.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] In asynchronous replication, the write operation is considered complete as soon as local storage acknowledges it.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Remote storage is updated with a small lag.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Performance is greatly increased, but in case of a local storage failure, the remote storage is not guaranteed to have the current copy of data (the most recent data may be lost).
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Semi-synchronous replication typically considers a write operation complete when acknowledged by local storage and received or logged by the remote server.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] The actual remote write is performed asynchronously, resulting in better performance but remote storage will lag behind the local storage, so that there is no guarantee of durability (i.e., seamless transparency) in the case of local storage failure.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Point-in-time replication produces periodic snapshots which are replicated instead of primary storage.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] This is intended to replicate only the changed data instead of the entire volume.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] As less information is replicated using this method, replication can occur over less-expensive bandwidth links such as iSCSI or T1 instead of fiberoptic lines.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Many distributed filesystems use replication to ensure fault tolerance and avoid a single point of failure.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Many commercial synchronous replication systems do not freeze when the remote replica fails or loses connection – behaviour which guarantees zero data loss – but proceed to operate locally, losing the desired zero recovery point objective.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Techniques of wide-area network (WAN) optimization can be applied to address the limits imposed by latency.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] File-based replication conducts data replication at the logical level (i.e., individual data files) rather than at the storage block level.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] There are many different ways of performing this, which almost exclusively rely on software.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] A kernel driver (specifically a filter driver) can be used to intercept calls to the filesystem functions, capturing any activity as it occurs.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] This uses the same type of technology that real-time active virus checkers employ.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] At this level, logical file operations are captured like file open, write, delete, etc.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] The kernel driver transmits these commands to another process, generally over a network to a different machine, which will mimic the operations of the source machine.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Like block-level storage replication, the file-level replication allows both synchronous and asynchronous modes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] In synchronous mode, write operations on the source machine are held and not allowed to occur until the destination machine has acknowledged the successful replication.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Synchronous mode is less common with file replication products although a few solutions exist.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] File-level replication solutions allow for informed decisions about replication based on the location and type of the file.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] For example, temporary files or parts of a filesystem that hold no business value could be excluded.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] The data transmitted can also be more granular; if an application writes 100 bytes, only the 100 bytes are transmitted instead of a complete disk block (generally 4,096 bytes).
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] This substantially reduces the amount of data sent from the source machine and the storage burden on the destination machine.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Drawbacks of this software-only solution include the requirement for implementation and maintenance on the operating system level, and an increased burden on the machine's processing power.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Similarly to database transaction logs, many file systems have the ability to journal their activity.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] The journal can be sent to another machine, either periodically or in real time by streaming.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] On the replica side, the journal can be used to play back file system modifications.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] One of the notable implementations is Microsoft's System Center Data Protection Manager (DPM), released in 2005, which performs periodic updates but does not offer real-time replication.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] This is the process of comparing the source and destination file systems and ensuring that the destination matches the source.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] The key benefit is that such solutions are generally free or inexpensive.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] The downside is that the process of synchronizing them is quite system-intensive, and consequently this process generally runs infrequently.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] One of the notable implementations is rsync.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] In a paging operating system, pages in a paging file are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] In IBM's VSAM, index data are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Another example of using replication appears in distributed shared memory systems, where many nodes of the system share the same page of memory.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] This usually means that each node has a separate copy (replica) of a specific page.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Many classical approaches to replication are based on a primary-backup model where one device or process has unilateral control over one or more other processes or devices.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] For example, the primary might perform some computation, streaming a log of updates to a backup (standby) process, which can then take over if the primary fails.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] This approach is common for replicating databases, despite the risk that if a portion of the log is lost during a failure, the backup might not be in a state identical to the primary, and transactions could then be lost.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] A weakness of primary-backup schemes is that only one is actually performing operations.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Fault-tolerance is gained, but the identical backup system doubles the costs.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] 1985, the distributed systems research community began to explore alternative methods of replicating data.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] An outgrowth of this work was the emergence of schemes in which a group of replicas could cooperate, with each process acting as a backup while also handling a share of the workload.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Computer scientist Jim Gray analyzed multi-primary replication schemes under the transactional model and published a widely cited paper skeptical of the approach "The Dangers of Replication and a Solution".
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] He argued that unless the data splits in some natural way so that the database can be treated as *n* disjoint sub-databases, concurrency control conflicts will result in seriously degraded performance and the group of replicas will probably slow as a function of *n*.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Gray suggested that the most common approaches are likely to result in degradation that scales as *O(n³)*.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] His solution, which is to partition the data, is only viable in situations where data actually has a natural partitioning key.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] In the 1985–1987, the virtual synchrony model was proposed and emerged as a widely adopted standard (it was used in the Isis Toolkit, Horus, Transis, Ensemble, Totem, Spread, C-Ensemble, Phoenix and Quicksilver systems, and is the basis for the CORBA fault-tolerant computing standard).
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Virtual synchrony permits a multi-primary approach in which a group of processes cooperates to parallelize some aspects of request processing.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] The scheme can only be used for some forms of in-memory data, but can provide linear speedups in the size of the group.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] A number of modern products support similar schemes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] For example, the Spread Toolkit supports this same virtual synchrony model and can be used to implement a multi-primary replication scheme; it would also be possible to use C-Ensemble or Quicksilver in this manner.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] WANdisco permits active replication where every node on a network is an exact copy or replica and hence every node on the network is active at one time; this scheme is optimized for use in a wide area network (WAN).
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Modern multi-primary replication protocols optimize for the common failure-free operation.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] Chain replication is a popular family of such protocols.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] State-of-the-art protocol variants of chain replication offer high throughput and strong consistency by arranging replicas in a chain for writes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] This approach enables local reads on all replica nodes but has high latency for writes that must traverse multiple nodes sequentially.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] A more recent multi-primary protocol, Hermes, combines cache-coherent-inspired invalidations and logical timestamps to achieve strong consistency with local reads and high-performance writes from all replicas.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] During fault-free operation, its broadcast-based writes are non-conflicting and commit after just one multicast round-trip to replica nodes.
[src:apache-zookeeper/replication-computing] This design results in high throughput and low latency for both reads and writes.
